{
  "id": "projectile-drag",
  "title": "Projectile with air resistance: when the parabola breaks",
  "topic": "projectile",
  "slug": "with-drag",
  "scenario": "The same launch — $v_0 = 30$ m/s at $\\theta = 45°$ — but now with quadratic air resistance $F = b\\,|v|\\,v$. There is no closed-form trajectory: the path is solved by numerical integration. Slide the drag up from zero and watch the clean parabola (dashed) deform — the range shrinks and the descent steepens.",
  "regime": 2,
  "constants": {
    "g": -10.0,
    "v0": 30.0,
    "theta_deg": 45.0,
    "m": 1.0
  },
  "initial_conditions": {
    "x0": 0.0,
    "y0": 0.0,
    "v0": 30.0,
    "theta_deg": 45.0
  },
  "assumptions": [
    {
      "claim": "Quadratic air resistance $F = b\\,|v|\\,v$ opposing the velocity vector (the author-asserted drag model).",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "$g = -10$ m/s², up positive; point mass launched from and landing at the same height.",
      "kind": "model"
    },
    {
      "claim": "No closed form exists, so the path is solved by numerical (4th-order Runge–Kutta) integration — converged to better than 1 mm and machine-checked against the equation of motion.",
      "kind": "model"
    }
  ],
  "algebra": {
    "steps": [
      {
        "label": "Where the algebra-based course stops",
        "latex": "R = \\frac{v_0^2\\sin 2\\theta}{|g|}\\quad\\text{— does NOT apply: with drag, } a \\text{ is not constant}",
        "prose": "The clean projectile formulas assume the only force is gravity. Air resistance grows with speed and changes direction along the path, so the acceleration is never constant and there is no algebra formula for the range. At best you're told drag 'reduces' it."
      }
    ],
    "result": {
      "range_with_drag": {
        "label": "Range with drag",
        "unit": "m",
        "value": 55.099957,
        "display": "55.1",
        "symbolic_latex": ""
      },
      "range_no_drag": {
        "label": "Range without drag $v_0^2\\sin2\\theta/|g|$",
        "unit": "m",
        "value": 90.0,
        "display": "90",
        "symbolic_latex": ""
      },
      "range_lost": {
        "label": "Range lost to drag",
        "unit": "m",
        "value": 34.900043,
        "display": "34.9",
        "symbolic_latex": ""
      },
      "max_height_drag": {
        "label": "Max height with drag",
        "unit": "m",
        "value": 16.860456,
        "display": "16.86",
        "symbolic_latex": ""
      }
    }
  },
  "calculus": {
    "steps": [
      {
        "label": "Newton's second law with quadratic drag (a vector ODE)",
        "latex": "m\\,\\dot{\\mathbf v} = m\\mathbf g - b\\,|\\mathbf v|\\,\\mathbf v \\;\\Longrightarrow\\; \\begin{cases} \\dot v_x = -\\tfrac{b}{m}|\\mathbf v|v_x \\\\ \\dot v_y = g - \\tfrac{b}{m}|\\mathbf v|v_y \\end{cases}",
        "prose": "Drag opposes the velocity vector and grows with the square of the speed. The two components are now coupled through $|\\mathbf v| = \\sqrt{v_x^2+v_y^2}$ — they are no longer independent, and there is no elementary closed form."
      },
      {
        "label": "Integrate numerically (the only road in)",
        "latex": "\\mathbf s_{n+1} = \\mathbf s_n + \\tfrac{h}{6}(k_1+2k_2+2k_3+k_4)",
        "prose": "Step the state forward with a fourth-order Runge–Kutta integrator. The producer checks the result is converged (halving the step barely moves it) and that it satisfies the equation of motion — the same 'verification is the product', now for a numerical solution."
      },
      {
        "label": "What drag does to the path",
        "latex": "\\text{range} < \\frac{v_0^2\\sin2\\theta}{|g|},\\qquad \\text{descent steeper than ascent}",
        "prose": "Slide the drag up from zero and watch the parabola (dashed) deform: the range shrinks, the peak drops and shifts, and the fall is steeper than the rise because the projectile has lost speed to drag. At $b=0$ the numerical path lands exactly on the parabola.",
        "emphasis": true
      }
    ]
  },
  "proof": {
    "kind": "governing",
    "heading": "No closed form exists — so the path is integrated numerically and machine-verified against the equation of motion.",
    "checked_by": "sympy",
    "holds": true,
    "detail": "integrate $\\dot{\\mathbf v} = \\mathbf g - (b/m)|\\mathbf v|\\mathbf v$ by RK4; check step-convergence; check the equation-of-motion residual; check $b=0$ recovers the exact parabola",
    "checks": [
      {
        "key": "converged",
        "tier": "numeric",
        "holds": true,
        "claim": "The path is RK4-converged: halving the step changes the range by less than $1$ mm."
      },
      {
        "key": "solves_eom",
        "tier": "numeric",
        "holds": true,
        "claim": "The path solves $m\\,\\dot{\\mathbf v} = m\\mathbf g - b|\\mathbf v|\\mathbf v$ (max residual $6.4e-06$ m/s²)."
      },
      {
        "key": "recovers_parabola",
        "tier": "numeric",
        "holds": true,
        "claim": "At $b=0$ the numerical path reproduces the exact drag-free parabola (range matches $v_0^2\\sin2\\theta/|g|$)."
      },
      {
        "key": "drag_shortens",
        "tier": "numeric",
        "holds": true,
        "claim": "Drag shortens the range: $55.1$ m vs $90.0$ m undamped, and the descent is steeper than the ascent."
      }
    ]
  },
